  "prompt": "What business model does olx use?",
  "response": "OLX uses a **classifieds advertising business model.**\n\nHere's a breakdown of how it works:\n\n*   **Free Listings:** Primarily, OLX allows users to post listings for items they want to sell or services they want to offer for **free**. This is the core of their user acquisition strategy.\n*   **Premium/Featured Listings:**  They generate revenue by offering **premium or featured listings** that sellers can pay for to increase the visibility of their ads. These paid options typically include:\n    *   **Bump-up:**  Bring the ad back to the top of the listings.\n    *   **Highlight:** Make the ad stand out with visual cues (different color, larger size, etc.).\n    *   **Top Ads:**  Display the ad prominently in a special \"Top Ads\" section.\n*   **Targeted Advertising:** OLX also generates revenue through **displaying targeted advertisements** from other businesses on their platform. These ads are often relevant to the categories of items being sold on the site.\n*   **Subscription services:** In some regions and categories, OLX may offer subscription packages to sellers that allow them to post more ads or access premium features.\n*   **Partnerships and Integrations:** In some markets, OLX may also have partnerships with other businesses, such as real estate agencies or auto dealerships, and may receive revenue through lead generation or commission-based arrangements.\n*   **OLX Pay (in some regions):** OLX might offer a secure payment gateway (OLX Pay) in certain regions. While the primary function is to facilitate safer transactions, OLX might earn a small transaction fee for each transaction processed through the platform.\n\n**In summary, OLX's main source of revenue is through premium advertising features that sellers pay for to get more visibility for their listings. They primarily offer a free service to attract a large user base, which they can then monetize through paid ads and other premium services.**\n",
